localStorage and sessionStorage, part of the web storage API, are two great tools to save key/value pairs locally. If you click the save button at the top of this post, localStorage is whatâ€™s used to store your saved posts.

Both localStorage and sessionStorage offer advantages compared to using cookies:

The data is saved locally only and canâ€™t be read by the server, which eliminates the security issue that cookies present.
It allows for much more data to be saved (10Mb for most browsers).
Itâ€™s simpler to use and the syntax is very straightforward.
Itâ€™s also supported in all modern browsers, so you can use it today without an issue. Obviously, since the data canâ€™t be read on the server, cookies still have a use, especially when it comes to authentication.

